					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">There <em>might</em> be Genesis-specific programs that can help you with this, but since the Gen &amp; PCE/Turbografx-16 are both 9-bit, perhaps one piece of software can help you with ideas:<br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://somanybits.com/i2pce/download.html">http://somanybits.com/i2pce/download.html</a><!-- m --><br /><br />Though it's not the easiest-to-use or most bug-free piece of software, it does convert high-colour bitmaps (dumbly) down to a # of palettes.  The 2nd-to-last tab will let you limit it to 4 palette banks.<br /><br />The ideal convertor would let you use shadow/highlight overlays to multiply the # of colours that could be achieved in your pic.<br /><br />Anyway, some other techniques for smoothing out ugliness would be to dither the image before reduction to indexed colours:<br /><img src="http://www.chrismcovell.com/images/RemapExample.png" alt="Image" /><br /><br />I also made some curves for Photoshop that posterize to 9-bit colour with 2 different biases:<br /><img src="http://www.chrismcovell.com/images/Example-Improved.png" alt="Image" /><br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.chrismcovell.com/data/PCE_Remapping_Curves.zip">http://www.chrismcovell.com/data/PCE_Re ... Curves.zip</a><!-- m --><br /><br />You might want to stick with vertical dithering only, since that works best on the Genesis through composite.</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.chrismcovell.com">http://www.chrismcovell.com</a><!-- m --></div>
